                    access_token="TEXTOFACCESSTOKENHERE",

Rate Limiting

  Even though APIs are far more convenient to use than screenscraping, they also prevent you from collecting too much data within too short a time frame (for a variety of reasons).

Find the Rate Limits

 

getCurRateLimitInfo()

...And if we want to look:

 

head(twitter_data)

Let's use the data we scraped...

 

Now let's take the data we scraped earlier and create a network of celebrities. First, we create a blank data frame to store data we get from the Twitter API:

twitter_network_data<-as.data.frame(NULL)

Figure out how many rows we have to scrape:

z<-nrow(twitter_data)

Our Loop

 

for(i in 1:z){
  user <- getUser(twitter_data$twitter_handles[i])
  people_user_follows <- user$getFriends()
  people_user_follows<-twListToDF(people_user_follows)
  people_user_follows$name_of_user<-twitter_data$twitter_handles[i]
  twitter_network_data<-rbind(twitter_network_data, people_user_follows)
  Sys.sleep(60)
  print(i)
}

Working with APIs from "scratch"

  What if you want to collect data from an API that does not have an R package?

Let's pretend there is no R package for Google Maps

 

We can look for patterns in API queries in the documentation:

https://maps.googleapis.com/maps/api/geocode/json?address=Durham,NorthCarolina&sensor=false

In this case, address goes between the first = and the &

Let's write a function

 

findGPS <- function(address) {
 beginning <- "http://maps.google.com/maps/api/geocode/json?"
 paster <- paste0(beginning,"address=", address, "&sensor=false")
 return(URLencode(paster))
}

Let's try our function

 

findGPS("Durham, North Carolina")

[1] "http://maps.google.com/maps/api/geocode/json?address=Durham,%20North%20Carolina&sensor=false"

Sweet sweet JSON!

 

Now we need to get the JSON

  We need the RJSONIO package- or alternatively the more recent jsonlite package:

library(RJSONIO)
page<-findGPS("Durham, North Carolina")
gpscoordinates <- fromJSON(page)
latitude <- gpscoordinates$results[[1]]$geometry$location["lat"]
longitude <- gpscoordinates$results[[1]]$geometry$location["lng"]
gps<-c(latitude, longitude)
gps

One Final Tip: Unix Time/Dates

 

At some point you will probably need to work with time stamps- particularly if you collect data from a social media site

One Final Tip: Unix Time/Dates

 

Unix time is seconds that have elapsed since 1/1/1970. Handy because it is a consistent format that can be grouped easily, but most time stamps will look like dates. To handle these use strptime

x <- strptime(c("2006-01-08 10:07:52", "2006-08-07 19:33:02"),"%Y-%m-%d %H:%M:%S", tz = "EST5EDT")
x

[1] "2006-01-08 10:07:52 EST" "2006-08-07 19:33:02 EDT"
